      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon in quantum physics where two or more particles become linked in such a way that the state of one particle instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance separating them. This connection is so strong that the properties of one particle can be determined instantly by measuring the other, even if they are light-years apart. This is fundamentally different from classical correlation, where objects may be related, but their connection does not involve instantaneous influence over long distances. In classical physics, information transfer is limited by the speed of light, whereas in quantum entanglement, the connection between particles transcends this limit. This phenomenon challenges our traditional understanding of space and time and has significant implications for the development of quantum computing and quantum communication technologies.",
