    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, one of the pioneers of quantum physics. He used this phrase to express his discomfort and skepticism with the concept of quantum entanglement. Einstein, along with his colleagues Podolsky and Rosen, formulated the EPR paradox in 1935, which highlighted the strange nature of quantum entanglement and its apparent violation of the principle of locality. Locality is the idea that objects are only directly influenced by their immediate surroundings. The \"spooky\" aspect refers to the seemingly instantaneous connection between entangled particles, which seems to defy the conventional understanding of how the universe works. Einstein famously referred to this phenomenon as \"spooky\" because it challenged his belief in a deterministic universe, where cause and effect follow a clear, predictable path. Despite his reservations, quantum entanglement has been experimentally confirmed and is now a fundamental aspect of quantum mechanics, with practical applications in quantum computing, cryptography, and teleportation.",
      "source": "target",
